1
00:00:02,714 --> 00:00:08,163
Bahia holds the record for being the quickest of the Buddha's disciples to reach enlightenment.

2
00:00:09,467 --> 00:00:14,695
He only got a very brief training, a few words while the Buddha was on his alms round.

3
00:00:16,399 --> 00:00:23,413
These were the first and only words of Dhamma Bahia had ever heard, and yet he gained full enlightenment as he listened.

4
00:00:24,855 --> 00:00:26,257
It's an inspiring story.

5
00:00:28,364 --> 00:00:38,700
Bahia, we are told, was a respected recluse living by the seashore and known as Bahia of the bark cloth because his robes were made from bark.

6
00:00:40,462 --> 00:00:53,982
One day he pondered his own level of spiritual understanding, asking, Now, of those who in this world are Arahants or have entered the path leading to Aranthantship, am I one?

7
00:00:55,042 --> 00:01:07,483
He couldn't answer this, and we're told that a compassionate deva appeared before him saying, You, Bahia, are neither an Arahant nor have entered the path leading to Arahantship.

8
00:01:08,566 --> 00:01:13,795
You do not even have a practice whereby you can become an Arahant or enter that path.

9
00:01:15,191 --> 00:01:25,319
Bahia, we are told, was greatly chastened by this, but luckily not disheartened, and immediately asked where he could find an Arahant to teach him.

10
00:01:26,245 --> 00:01:33,460
The deva then tells him that the Buddha is currently living at Jeta's grove in Savati and teaching the Dhamma there.

11
00:01:34,522 --> 00:01:45,266
It's a long way away, some 1,200 miles, but Bahiya doesn't hesitate for a moment to set out and hurry as fast as he could to Savahi.

12
00:01:47,439 --> 00:01:51,545
When he gets to Jeta's grove, he is told that the Buddha is out on alms round.

13
00:01:52,606 --> 00:02:04,221
Not willing to wait another moment, Bahiya hurries out in pursuit, and upon finding the Buddha, throws himself down at his feet, exclaiming, Teach me the Dhamma, O blessed one.

14
00:02:05,063 --> 00:02:11,592
Teach me the Dhamma, O well-gone one, that will be for my long-term welfare and bliss.

15
00:02:14,322 --> 00:02:19,706
The Buddha at first refuses, saying that he is on alms round and not free to teach.

16
00:02:20,747 --> 00:02:28,215
Bahir repeats his request again and again, arguing that either his own or the Buddha's life could be ended at any moment.

17
00:02:29,855 --> 00:02:37,582
On the third request, the Buddha relents, saying, Then, Bahir, you should train yourself thus.

18
00:02:39,145 --> 00:02:41,747
In the seen there is only the seen.

19
00:02:42,622 --> 00:02:45,046
In the heard, only the heard.

20
00:02:46,329 --> 00:02:48,652
In the sensed, only the sensed.

21
00:02:49,876 --> 00:02:52,901
In the cognized, only the cognized.

22
00:02:54,043 --> 00:02:56,007
That is how you should train yourself.

23
00:02:56,998 --> 00:03:14,890
When for you there will only be the seen in the seen, only the heard in the heard, only the sensed in the sensed, only the cognized in the cognized, then, Bahia, there is no you in connection with that.

24
00:03:16,593 --> 00:03:21,622
When there is no you in connection with that, there is no you there.

25
00:03:22,867 --> 00:03:29,317
when there is no you there, then you are neither here nor there, nor anywhere in between.

26
00:03:30,838 --> 00:03:33,962
Just this is the end of suffering.

27
00:03:37,888 --> 00:03:42,693
As Bahiya listened to these words, the penny dropped and he was liberated.

28
00:03:44,836 --> 00:03:52,167
The Buddha went on his way and just as he had feared, Bahiya died having been attacked by a cow.

29
00:03:53,766 --> 00:04:01,217
When the Buddha later came across Bahia's body, he told his disciples to cremate this and erect a memorial.

30
00:04:02,437 --> 00:04:14,373
When they ask him about Bahia's destination, his future life, the Buddha replies that Bahia is totally unbound, meaning that he is liberated from suffering and rebirth.

31
00:04:18,774 --> 00:04:25,668
Before we look at the teaching at the core of the Sutta, I think it's helpful to paint a picture of Bahia for ourselves.

32
00:04:27,331 --> 00:04:39,535
One reason is that the teaching itself, as with so much of the Dhamma, invites us to deconstruct our normal understanding of reality, to see that we're not this, not that.

33
00:04:40,983 --> 00:04:51,552
Though this is essential, we also have to make an effort to reconstruct our understanding of reality where I am me and you are you and a dog is a dog and so on.

34
00:04:54,355 --> 00:05:03,764
This normal understanding is sometimes described as conventional reality whereas the deconstructed version is termed ultimate reality.

35
00:05:05,666 --> 00:05:10,011
The spiritual life requires that we navigate both levels peacefully.

36
00:05:12,302 --> 00:05:16,790
If we focus only on the ultimate level, this can lead to abstraction.

37
00:05:17,552 --> 00:05:18,894
We grow aloof from the world.

38
00:05:20,476 --> 00:05:28,589
If we engage with the story of Bahia, we warm up the teaching, bring our humanity to the forefront as we listen to the Dhamma.

39
00:05:29,987 --> 00:05:35,437
We can remember also that the Buddha always chose exactly the right teaching for each person.

40
00:05:36,600 --> 00:05:42,470
So if we can put ourselves in Bahia's shoes, we might hear the teachings in a more meaningful way.

41
00:05:47,158 --> 00:05:51,185
Some people think that Bahia was already highly developed spiritually.

42
00:05:52,297 --> 00:06:03,721
The Sutta doesn't give us much evidence for this, and I like the interpretation given by Buddha Gossa, an Indian monk and scholar who lived about a thousand years after the Buddha.

43
00:06:05,404 --> 00:06:11,959
Although interpretations lose some of the original purity, I think they have a value in their own right.

44
00:06:13,406 --> 00:06:25,245
The Buddha's presence, his calm, authority, body language, facial expression, all these would have added hugely to the words he spoke.

45
00:06:27,148 --> 00:06:36,562
As his real-life impact died away, myths and stories would have been added to the teachings as a human effort to retain some shadow of his presence.

46
00:06:38,095 --> 00:06:54,889
Of course, this will include cultural bias, and we don't have to take these as gospel, but they may make it easier for us to hear the teachings, to detect human warmth in them, rather than read them as a very dry manual of spiritual practice.

47
00:06:57,670 --> 00:07:06,605
Buddha Gossa gives us a prequel to the Sutta, suggesting that Bahiya was actually a novice in spiritual terms, even a bit of a fraud.

48
00:07:07,728 --> 00:07:10,812
Earlier, he and others had gone out to sea.

49
00:07:12,115 --> 00:07:19,728
Their ship sank and all his comrades were drowned, but Bahiya managed to cling to a plank and survive.

50
00:07:21,024 --> 00:07:27,793
Perhaps he was battered against rocks because by the time he made it ashore his clothes had been torn away.

51
00:07:30,156 --> 00:07:40,228
There was, and still is in parts of Asia, a tradition of making sheets of cloth from the sodden bark of trees and Bahia obviously had mastered this skill.

52
00:07:42,370 --> 00:07:47,656
From other suttas we see that being naked could lead to being despised and abused.

53
00:07:49,257 --> 00:08:03,699
It shows great strength of character that the half-drowned, bruised and battered Bahia managed to weave himself a cloak, a task few of us would have the patience to manage, even in the peak of health and well-being.

54
00:08:07,305 --> 00:08:11,451
By a lucky twist of faith, the barcloth works in his favour.

55
00:08:12,781 --> 00:08:22,634
When the local people saw him, they assumed he was an ascetic who had renounced clothing, even assuming he was fully enlightened and arahant.

56
00:08:23,814 --> 00:08:25,718
And so they started giving him food.

57
00:08:27,259 --> 00:08:39,075
Bahia realised he was on to a good thing and decided to eschew fine clothes and continue in his bark cloth, becoming known as Bahia of the Bark Cloth.

58
00:08:41,738 --> 00:08:45,683
Bahia then starts to wonder whether perhaps he is enlightened.

59
00:08:47,927 --> 00:08:59,225
There are reports of people mistaking themselves as enlightened because they've developed concentration to the extent that the hindrances are suppressed and they live in a state of bliss.

60
00:09:01,849 --> 00:09:03,951
Perhaps this was the case for Bahia.

61
00:09:05,193 --> 00:09:10,682
Perhaps all this talk of him being an Arahant persuaded him to dabble in meditation.

62
00:09:12,231 --> 00:09:15,275
He may well have had a mind that concentrated easily.

63
00:09:15,317 --> 00:09:19,982
The ease with which he picks up the Buddha's words suggests that.

64
00:09:22,046 --> 00:09:29,397
People with good concentration can achieve a state of jhana where the mind is absorbed in bliss.

65
00:09:31,360 --> 00:09:39,572
My guess is that Bahir fell into a jhana and then started wondering whether this bliss meant he was enlightened.

66
00:09:42,067 --> 00:09:50,240
Whatever about concentration, Bahia's spiritual assets certainly include energy, determination and perseverance.

67
00:09:52,303 --> 00:09:58,193
To have survived a situation where five companions perished shows a real strength of will.

68
00:09:59,976 --> 00:10:05,626
Bahia doesn't give up easily and once he realised that enlightenment involves

69
00:10:06,096 --> 00:10:11,985
his long-term welfare and bliss, he becomes single-mindedly focused on that goal.

70
00:10:15,990 --> 00:10:23,779
His zeal for liberation would have been spurred by acute awareness of mortality, as is pleased to the Buddha demonstrate.

71
00:10:25,682 --> 00:10:29,707
Buddha Gossa's story of near drowning gives a context for this.

72
00:10:31,628 --> 00:10:41,860
Although we might think of someone who suffered such a calamity as very unfortunate, in spiritual terms the shock of a near-death experience can be a great motivator.

73
00:10:43,322 --> 00:10:51,972
This is why we are encouraged to reflect on our mortality, go to cemeteries or view bodies decomposing, so as to make this more real.

74
00:10:54,316 --> 00:11:00,403
A near-death experience makes us painfully aware of the lack of any security in this life.

75
00:11:01,615 --> 00:11:07,864
We become disillusioned, perhaps depressed, lose interest in the pleasures of this world.

76
00:11:10,248 --> 00:11:19,801
When the Buddha realized the reality of sickness, old age and death, it is said that he returned to his palace like a lion pierced in the heart.

77
00:11:21,703 --> 00:11:25,750
That state of misery prompted the Buddha's spiritual life.

78
00:11:28,565 --> 00:11:35,375
Similarly, Bahía was determined to find a truth and security which transcended worldly life.

79
00:11:38,181 --> 00:11:41,365
Last but not least, Bahía had great faith.

80
00:11:42,788 --> 00:11:48,138
He doesn't waste any time doubting the Dhamma or his own potential for enlightenment.

81
00:11:49,460 --> 00:11:51,383
He goes straight for this prize

82
00:11:52,644 --> 00:11:58,052
With a kind of naive bull-headedness, he is only interested in learning from an Arahant.

83
00:11:59,114 --> 00:12:03,960
The fact that the Buddha is 1,200 miles away doesn't faze him for an instant.

84
00:12:07,804 --> 00:12:17,758
So Bahiya is an energetic, resourceful, determined character, and because of his near-death experience, strongly motivated to seek liberation.

85
00:12:19,644 --> 00:12:25,671
He's blessed with great faith in his own abilities, in the reality of enlightenment and in the Buddha.

86
00:12:27,873 --> 00:12:46,529
We see his single-mindedness again when, after his 1,200-mile journey, he doesn't dream of resting but immediately rushes out of Jeta's grove in pursuit of the Buddha, doesn't hesitate to interrupt his alms round, pesters him basically, until he receives the teachings.

87
00:12:50,424 --> 00:12:57,692
Bahia's story is a testament to the power of absolute one-pointed determination, faith and energy.

88
00:12:59,953 --> 00:13:04,599
But this do-or-die attitude is easily hijacked by greed.

89
00:13:06,341 --> 00:13:15,690
It needs to be balanced by an equal preference for calm and tranquillity, a sense that all is okay, just as it is.

90
00:13:18,606 --> 00:13:26,217
The Sutta gives this very beautiful description of the personage Bahiyya saw when he eventually caught up with the Buddha on his alms round.

91
00:13:28,881 --> 00:13:32,147
Serene and inspiring serene confidence.

92
00:13:33,067 --> 00:13:33,548
Calming.

93
00:13:34,590 --> 00:13:35,792
His senses at peace.

94
00:13:36,913 --> 00:13:38,034
His mind at peace.

95
00:13:39,317 --> 00:13:42,402
Having attained the utmost tranquility and poise.

96
00:13:43,582 --> 00:13:44,043
Tamed.

97
00:13:44,784 --> 00:13:45,285
Guarded.

98
00:13:45,947 --> 00:13:47,448
His senses restrained.

99
00:13:48,205 --> 00:13:50,490
a great one, Naga.

100
00:13:54,096 --> 00:14:08,626
This suggests that it was the very presence of the Buddha that allowed Bahir to calm down, bring his mind to rest upon the words the Buddha spoke, let them penetrate deep enough for full liberation.

101
00:14:13,923 --> 00:14:18,857
The Buddha's opening words, Bahiya, you should train yourself thus.

102
00:14:19,881 --> 00:14:24,456
Clarify that this is a training, not an account of what enlightenment is.

103
00:14:25,279 --> 00:14:30,729
The Buddha is not interested in philosophy for its own sake, an abstract definition of truth.

104
00:14:31,831 --> 00:14:34,615
Intellectual understanding isn't enough for liberation.

105
00:14:35,576 --> 00:14:40,083
The truth of enlightenment has to be lived and for this we need training.

106
00:14:41,186 --> 00:14:50,139
The Eightfold Path gives the full scope of training, addressing morality, views and attitudes as well as mental training.

107
00:14:52,279 --> 00:15:00,731
But in this very succinct teaching to Bahia, the Buddha focuses on the first step in the Eightfold Path, Right View.

108
00:15:00,772 --> 00:15:06,278
It's the way we see and understand the world that's most important.

109
00:15:07,039 --> 00:15:19,317
Everything else, our attitudes, our behaviour, our meditation, clicks into place if only we can be clear about what's actually happening in our moment-to-moment experience.

110
00:15:23,177 --> 00:15:28,326
The Buddha's next words to Bahiya describe the bare simplicity of the practice.

111
00:15:29,287 --> 00:15:32,251
In this scene, there is only the scene.

112
00:15:34,153 --> 00:15:37,158
When we see, we normally see something.

113
00:15:38,039 --> 00:15:40,604
We see a book, a tree, a person.

114
00:15:42,066 --> 00:15:45,932
And then we think about it, whether we read it, whether we'd like to read it.

115
00:15:46,712 --> 00:15:48,696
Same for the tree, the person.

116
00:15:50,126 --> 00:15:58,863
In reference to the scene, there is the scene plus all the thoughts and images and fond or unpleasant memories this provokes.

117
00:16:02,910 --> 00:16:06,937
Now it's possible of course that we don't properly register what we see.

118
00:16:08,167 --> 00:16:16,581
We vaguely scan our environment to avoid bumping into things, too preoccupied to bother giving full attention to the visual scene.

119
00:16:17,563 --> 00:16:20,269
No thoughts about books or trees or people are evoked.

120
00:16:21,311 --> 00:16:30,748
But if we were to be properly mindful, we would detect a quick judgment, labelling whatever we see as irrelevant, not worth thinking about.

121
00:16:31,437 --> 00:16:40,486
So there is the seen plus an aversive reaction, dismissing the sight as irrelevant and the consequent decision to ignore.

122
00:16:45,013 --> 00:16:52,201
Could we properly register the sight of a book, a tree, a person and not react, not add any thoughts?

123
00:16:53,461 --> 00:16:54,102
Difficult.

124
00:16:55,822 --> 00:17:02,839
The term is just seeing and is the spiritual practice we take from the Bahia Sutta.

125
00:17:04,823 --> 00:17:13,964
We train by noticing the proliferation of the thoughts or the desire to avert our eyes, find something more interesting.

126
00:17:15,835 --> 00:17:30,108
We then resist the habitual reactions, drop the thoughts, bring our eyes back to the visual object itself, its color, its shape, its bookness, reminding ourselves that we are seeing.

127
00:17:33,992 --> 00:17:40,559
When we train like this, we're coming back closer and closer to the raw experience of seeing.

128
00:17:42,380 --> 00:17:52,229
We're dropping our opinions and judgments and preconceptions about the things we see, getting more and more interested in the experience of seeing.

129
00:17:56,874 --> 00:18:11,086
Can you imagine living in a world where we didn't add a thousand judgments and stories, a thousand summary dismissals as irrelevant, as we let our eyes go about their business of scanning our surroundings?

130
00:18:13,750 --> 00:18:20,142
The teacher, Gilles Foncel, gives an example of this when he lived for a time in Morocco.

131
00:18:22,665 --> 00:18:25,531
He noticed his mind was much lighter than normal.

132
00:18:26,554 --> 00:18:28,616
He wasn't as troubled as usual in public.

133
00:18:30,180 --> 00:18:36,551
He eventually traced this to the fact that he wasn't reacting to people around him, making up stories about them.

134
00:18:38,219 --> 00:18:42,486
He realized it was because their clothing was so different to Western clothing.

135
00:18:43,688 --> 00:18:47,073
His habitual way of categorizing people just couldn't work.

136
00:18:48,695 --> 00:18:56,107
He had no way of judging, working out what their lives were like, who was rich, who was poor, who had what trade.

137
00:18:57,790 --> 00:19:00,935
So he was just seeing the people around him.

138
00:19:02,688 --> 00:19:13,362
This gave them a demonstration of the way we clog up our world and weigh ourselves down by adding layers and layers of unnecessary thought to whatever we see.

139
00:19:13,942 --> 00:19:17,346
He tasted the lightness of just seeing.

140
00:19:22,114 --> 00:19:25,798
The Buddha uses the same instructions for the other senses.

141
00:19:28,342 --> 00:19:30,805
In the hearing, there is only the hearing.

142
00:19:31,477 --> 00:19:37,266
In the sensing, this is understood to refer to sensations from odor and taste as well as body.

143
00:19:38,127 --> 00:19:39,710
There is only the sensing.

144
00:19:41,292 --> 00:19:44,238
In the cognizing, there is only the cognizing.

145
00:19:46,480 --> 00:19:47,804
The latter is interesting.

146
00:19:48,904 --> 00:19:56,116
Thoughts and images also have their place in very simple, non-reactive way of relating to the world.

147
00:19:58,190 --> 00:20:10,285
The thought book could arise on seeing a book, but no further thoughts are provoked about whether or not we've read the book or should read it or any other thought stream.

148
00:20:13,147 --> 00:20:24,821
At the very essence of seeing, hearing, sensing, there aren't thoughts, but simple sensations of colour or pressure or vibrations on the eardrum.

149
00:20:27,433 --> 00:20:40,490
But to interact in an intelligent way with these, we need to allow several sensations be processed by the mind so as to form perceptions and concepts like book, tree, person.

150
00:20:42,372 --> 00:20:47,238
This is happening all the time in the background as we go about our daily business.

151
00:20:49,160 --> 00:20:57,069
I got a glimpse into the extent of background processing going on in my mind one time as I walked into the bathroom of my apartment.

152
00:20:58,957 --> 00:21:02,243
Normally the light switch also turns on a fan.

153
00:21:03,807 --> 00:21:08,457
But when I pressed the switch this time, the light came on but the fan didn't.

154
00:21:10,079 --> 00:21:12,726
I started hearing the fan nonetheless.

155
00:21:14,189 --> 00:21:20,121
In fact, I heard every little nuance of its whirring and buzzing as I'd never heard them before.

156
00:21:21,484 --> 00:21:28,859
That's because I was listening properly for the first time, knowing something was unusual but unable to work out what.

157
00:21:30,823 --> 00:21:42,767
It took a couple of seconds to realize that this was a mental sound playing in my mind, a memory of what the fan sounded like, not a real sound impacting on my ears.

158
00:21:44,401 --> 00:21:54,876
My mind had made its own very accurate recording of the sound of the fan, and had probably been playing this every time I'd pressed that switch for the past several years.

159
00:21:57,140 --> 00:22:08,277
Perhaps this is my mind's way of policing the environment, projecting whatever it anticipates onto the screen of consciousness so that the real data can be compared to the memory.

160
00:22:10,599 --> 00:22:13,664
I don't know the rationale behind the mental recording,

161
00:22:14,539 --> 00:22:23,352
but it showed me how much quiet, clever and accurate processing the mind can do in the background of our lives.

162
00:22:30,080 --> 00:22:41,576
The training instructions given to Bahia describe the body and mind carrying out their functions quite normally seeing, hearing, sensing, cognizing.

163
00:22:42,755 --> 00:22:45,619
It's only our usual reactivity that's missing.

164
00:22:47,644 --> 00:22:51,089
And reactivity, remember, involves craving.

165
00:22:53,012 --> 00:22:56,298
We crave more of whatever sensations are deemed pleasant.

166
00:22:57,039 --> 00:22:59,364
We crave to get rid of those deemed unpleasant.

167
00:23:00,266 --> 00:23:03,632
We crave to ignore those we deem neutral.

168
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:07,301
We see the book.

169
00:23:08,702 --> 00:23:16,730
If we're an avid reader, this will be labelled pleasant and craving perks us up as we register the pleasure on offer here.

170
00:23:18,412 --> 00:23:25,137
But if we loathe reading, then the image will be labelled unpleasant and we crave to be rid of this irritation.

171
00:23:26,699 --> 00:23:30,522
If books mean little or nothing to us, we label the sight as neutral.

172
00:23:31,423 --> 00:23:36,488
We crave to ignore the sight, not to waste time letting our eyes rest on this irrelevance.

173
00:23:38,105 --> 00:23:41,209
We're seldom aware of the craving underlying neutral feelings.

174
00:23:42,130 --> 00:23:48,798
But if you try resting your eyes on some fairly bland surface, you might soon feel a level of impatience.

175
00:23:50,040 --> 00:23:53,244
Your eyes will want to rove around, see something else.

176
00:23:54,426 --> 00:23:56,068
Your mind will probably want to think.

177
00:23:57,490 --> 00:24:03,318
This gives an insight into how deeply we crave to ignore sights we feel as neutral.

178
00:24:06,926 --> 00:24:11,011
Craving leads on to grasping, sometimes called clinging.

179
00:24:12,554 --> 00:24:17,880
This is where we establish a sense of self, a central headquarters for experience.

180
00:24:19,082 --> 00:24:27,872
The headquarters we call me or I or mine can now marshal our physical and mental energies so as to fulfil craving.

181
00:24:30,890 --> 00:24:40,426
In Bahia's training instructions, the Buddha clarifies that the goal is not to grasp, not to construct a sense of self, a central headquarters.

182
00:24:42,465 --> 00:25:02,647
When for you, Bahia, there is in the seen only the seen, in the heard only the heard, in the sensed only the sensed, in the cognized only the cognized, then, Bahia, there is no you to be found in relation to that.

183
00:25:08,054 --> 00:25:10,936
We practice non-grasping in Vipassana.

184
00:25:12,857 --> 00:25:16,801
When we become equanimous, thoughts and feelings come and go.

185
00:25:17,801 --> 00:25:21,625
We watch our dramas without getting caught up.

186
00:25:21,645 --> 00:25:24,828
We have the sense of being the observer of our own experience.

187
00:25:26,490 --> 00:25:28,932
We're not interfering, just watching.

188
00:25:31,355 --> 00:25:36,499
Bhante uses the analogy of a birdwatcher concealed within a hide.

189
00:25:38,361 --> 00:25:42,003
At times, even the observer disappears.

190
00:25:43,891 --> 00:25:49,980
There is breathing, feeling, sensing, cognizing, but no one watching all this.

191
00:25:52,044 --> 00:25:54,688
Experience is not centered around me.

192
00:25:56,330 --> 00:26:00,557
Awareness doesn't seem to be located within my body as it normally is.

193
00:26:01,839 --> 00:26:04,924
When a bird sings, we're just aware of the sound.

194
00:26:06,287 --> 00:26:11,535
Usually it's me in here hearing the bird out there.

195
00:26:13,202 --> 00:26:16,425
Now there's only the sound without any reference to me at all.

196
00:26:17,967 --> 00:26:25,994
We can still recognize the sound as bird song, and we can still locate the sound, know roughly where it comes from.

197
00:26:26,035 --> 00:26:34,001
All the essential perceptions and cognitions needed to negotiate the world are functioning perfectly.

198
00:26:35,523 --> 00:26:41,269
We've just stopped referring everything back to me, the hearer, me, the observer,

199
00:26:44,894 --> 00:26:47,436
In the hearing, there is only the hearing.

200
00:26:47,497 --> 00:26:55,945
There is hearing, recognizing, but no one hearing, no one recognizing.

201
00:26:58,048 --> 00:27:06,897
We're no longer automatically mapping sensations and feelings into concepts like me, you, self, not self.

202
00:27:08,779 --> 00:27:10,682
As the Buddha told Bahiya,

203
00:27:11,573 --> 00:27:20,064
When in the hearing there is only the hearing, then Vahiyya, there is no you in relation to that.

204
00:27:24,710 --> 00:27:37,767
While Vahiyya grasped all this in a moment, we can make an effort to follow in his footsteps by bringing to mind concepts of you or that when the mind is steady in meditation.

205
00:27:39,349 --> 00:27:43,796
It's easiest to focus on just one, say it's the concept you.

206
00:27:45,438 --> 00:27:50,105
In my experience, a strong desire to understand the concept is stirred.

207
00:27:51,767 --> 00:27:55,992
Tensions build in the body and the mind starts to polarize.

208
00:27:58,076 --> 00:28:06,386
I'm experiencing the effort needed, by an unenlightened being anyhow, to frame and hold a concept.

209
00:28:08,189 --> 00:28:15,898
The calming factors, especially tranquility and equanimity, balance the polarizing effect.

210
00:28:17,942 --> 00:28:23,148
I realize that I have to continually let go of the concept for any peace.

211
00:28:25,612 --> 00:28:34,263
A very vague you takes shape as an image, as if I'm looking at myself in a mirror, then dissolves again.

212
00:28:36,099 --> 00:28:43,128
The dissolving is experienced as peaceful, pleasant, but tinged with sadness as if I'm saying goodbye.

213
00:28:45,111 --> 00:28:50,959
Then the desire to form the concept, to know this you, starts the process again.

214
00:28:51,019 --> 00:29:05,938
It becomes clear that the desire is associated with a sense of self, an I who wants to know this vague, unstable you, which is continually fading away.

215
00:29:10,069 --> 00:29:14,394
This practice helps us make peace with the conceptual mind.

216
00:29:16,298 --> 00:29:22,484
It's the attachment to concepts like you and that which snares us in dukkha.

217
00:29:24,587 --> 00:29:31,676
As we train ourselves to steady the mind around these concepts, we slowly purify our attachments.

218
00:29:33,479 --> 00:29:36,803
We learn that concepts aren't ultimate reality.

219
00:29:38,268 --> 00:29:47,922
The only reality in the midst of a concept like you are the sensations and feelings experienced as I try to hold the concept in mind.

220
00:29:50,165 --> 00:29:52,269
We have a preference for pleasant feelings.

221
00:29:53,931 --> 00:29:59,179
These are associated with the relaxation, the letting go of the concept.

222
00:30:00,678 --> 00:30:02,401
It's lucky we're designed like that.

223
00:30:03,883 --> 00:30:08,891
Our preference for tranquility won't let us get too attached to our concepts.

224
00:30:11,954 --> 00:30:13,897
And yet we want to know ourselves.

225
00:30:16,082 --> 00:30:22,010
Dhamma Chanda can be described as the desire to know our true nature.

226
00:30:23,797 --> 00:30:27,901
This desire springs from wisdom and drives the spiritual life.

227
00:30:29,063 --> 00:30:32,666
But because of attachment, tanha gets mixed in.

228
00:30:33,186 --> 00:30:35,890
We want to gain something out of all this effort.

229
00:30:36,590 --> 00:30:37,632
Perhaps it's power.

230
00:30:38,073 --> 00:30:42,416
We want to be in control of experience, not at the mercy of circumstances.

231
00:30:43,337 --> 00:30:45,921
Perhaps it's the desire to love or be loved.

232
00:30:46,821 --> 00:30:49,365
Perhaps we want to save ourselves from dukkha.

233
00:30:49,987 --> 00:30:55,734
In pure form, these desires are all worthy aspects of Dhamma Chanda.

234
00:30:57,478 --> 00:31:00,721
But delusion allows them get hijacked by greed.

235
00:31:02,223 --> 00:31:11,978
Delusion tells us we are or could be that entity who is in control, who loves and is loved, who saves the world from dukkha.

236
00:31:14,894 --> 00:31:29,974
Only as we sit still, burning with desire in Vipassana, can we start to separate out tanha, the greed for spiritual progress, from dhamma chanda, the wise desire to be present with experience, just as it is.

237
00:31:32,138 --> 00:31:42,993
The desire to know our true nature stirs us to frame a concept like you, while tranquility and equanimity persuade us to let go of the concept.

238
00:31:44,137 --> 00:31:45,098
It's a tight rope.

239
00:31:47,422 --> 00:31:54,430
Because of our deep attachment to conceptual thought, tranquility often presents the wisest option.

240
00:31:55,971 --> 00:32:03,040
However, we can go overboard here, come to dread and deplore conceptual thought because it's so disturbing.

241
00:32:04,702 --> 00:32:07,125
It is useful to be able to think, however.

242
00:32:07,685 --> 00:32:12,271
Even an Arahant might need to think about issues when deciding on a course of action.

243
00:32:13,737 --> 00:32:25,476
The story of Brahma advising the Buddha to teach the Dharma could be interpreted as the Buddha's rational thinking mind in conversation with his enlightened nature.

244
00:32:27,439 --> 00:32:31,724
Brahma in Indian mythology represents the wisest being.

245
00:32:34,369 --> 00:32:39,136
While he lived, the Buddha had being nature, human nature.

246
00:32:40,483 --> 00:32:47,711
The Buddha's being, because it is no longer deluded, is the wisest being, is Brahma.

247
00:32:50,615 --> 00:33:00,546
Thus, even an Arahant will at times need to generate concepts so as to weigh up matters, decide whether a course of action is worthwhile.

248
00:33:00,586 --> 00:33:09,174
The Buddha used concepts like I and me and you and so on all the time as he taught.

249
00:33:10,571 --> 00:33:21,509
In particular, he taught the practice of metta, to cherish and care for ourselves as individuals, to care for each being as an individual being.

250
00:33:23,380 --> 00:33:41,047
Being able to frame the millions of colours and sounds and sensations and feelings that arise each moment as concepts, me, mine, you, yours, is a very important aspect of human intellect and interaction.

251
00:33:42,189 --> 00:33:47,817
And, at least on this side of liberation, is a necessary basis for compassion.

252
00:33:50,785 --> 00:33:58,337
Thus, we undertake the practice of forming concepts in meditation as part of the path of purification.

253
00:34:00,301 --> 00:34:15,307
Although we might sense conceptualization as disturbing a more peaceful meditation, and we might quickly detect ourselves grasping onto concepts like you and I, we cannot afford to shirk away from the task.

254
00:34:17,195 --> 00:34:21,489
Otherwise, we simply get attached to tranquility and equanimity.

255
00:34:23,556 --> 00:34:30,478
This can lead to the delusion which marked the start of Bahia's journey, wondering whether perhaps he was enlightened.

256
00:34:35,047 --> 00:34:46,362
Working with the conceptual mind in Vipassana links to the teaching on the destruction of craving, where the Buddha advises us to understand experience within the reflection.

257
00:34:47,202 --> 00:34:48,684
This has come to be.

258
00:34:48,704 --> 00:34:52,829
This anger has come to be.

259
00:34:52,869 --> 00:34:55,311
This peace has come to be.

260
00:34:55,351 --> 00:34:58,255
This boredom has come to be.

261
00:34:58,275 --> 00:35:01,039
This itching has come to be.

262
00:35:03,094 --> 00:35:06,338
Every experience can be understood within the phrase.

263
00:35:08,621 --> 00:35:16,130
At times, when we watch an experience, say it's an itching sensation, we find that it fades away.

264
00:35:17,632 --> 00:35:18,612
What are we left with?

265
00:35:20,215 --> 00:35:28,764
Our attention can be riveted, focused on the spot where the itching faded, but we can't name what's holding attention anymore.

266
00:35:30,769 --> 00:35:33,996
The desire to describe is felt as disturbing.

267
00:35:35,798 --> 00:35:49,503
As the body and mind relax, letting go of the desire to think, the focus for awareness broadens, sensing peace in the broad expanse of a mind that isn't interested in thinking.

268
00:35:52,505 --> 00:36:02,978
This is a mind that is, for a few moments anyhow, content within itself, not trying to work things out, sort out this from that.

269
00:36:05,099 --> 00:36:08,784
After a while, restlessness or some other hindrance sets in.

270
00:36:10,706 --> 00:36:17,635
I often find the mind flickering at what seems like its outer border, trying to expand the circle of awareness.

271
00:36:18,965 --> 00:36:31,344
As it peeks momentarily into what we might call the outer darkness, it labels the darkness as that, because it seems beyond its grasp, objective, external.

272
00:36:33,527 --> 00:36:40,719
A moment later, it flickers towards a brightness associated with a physical sensation and pleasant feeling.

273
00:36:42,150 --> 00:36:49,481
It labels the brightness as this because it feels like me, mine, eminently graspable.

274
00:36:51,666 --> 00:37:00,860
These flickering movements of mind give us a chance to study the next reflection Buddha recommends in the teaching on the destruction of craving.

275
00:37:03,143 --> 00:37:06,268
This arise with that as nutriment.

276
00:37:08,358 --> 00:37:15,471
We grasp at pleasant feelings, think of them as mine, because the mind is not satisfied with its own limits.

277
00:37:17,153 --> 00:37:23,525
It senses something beyond itself, something external, something it can call that.

278
00:37:25,108 --> 00:37:30,416
But the concept that opens the door to the concept this.

279
00:37:31,949 --> 00:37:39,400
Our logical mind demands that if there's something external, then there has to be something internal looking out.

280
00:37:40,621 --> 00:37:45,668
And so we start grasping towards the body, feelings, perceptions, etc.

281
00:37:46,349 --> 00:37:47,652
as me and mine.

282
00:37:48,594 --> 00:37:50,396
We become the observer again.

283
00:37:50,416 --> 00:38:01,112
To let go of that sense of being the observer, we need to make peace with the limits of our knowledge.

284
00:38:03,032 --> 00:38:09,081
Can we resist the temptation to look beyond what's right here, right now?

285
00:38:10,702 --> 00:38:14,248
Challenging, but a worthy practice.

286
00:38:20,056 --> 00:38:31,572
The last thing the Buddha says to Bahiya is, when there is no you there, then you are neither here nor there, nor anywhere in between.

287
00:38:32,969 --> 00:38:36,135
Just this is the end of suffering.

288
00:38:41,909 --> 00:38:48,565
When the mind isn't forming the concept me, then there's no location for the self.

289
00:38:50,400 --> 00:38:52,302
There can still be spatial knowledge.

290
00:38:53,545 --> 00:39:00,012
We can locate books and trees and other visible objects as well as the source of sounds.

291
00:39:01,233 --> 00:39:03,155
We can move our body appropriately.

292
00:39:04,157 --> 00:39:06,820
We don't get our arms mixed up with our legs.

293
00:39:08,581 --> 00:39:14,248
It's just that the mind isn't generating a focal point for me in the world.

294
00:39:17,485 --> 00:39:23,451
Normally, we locate ourselves as here, somewhere within our body.

295
00:39:25,112 --> 00:39:29,536
When we see a tree, we think of ourselves as the one who sees.

296
00:39:31,759 --> 00:39:38,786
Focusing more closely, we sense that we are identifying with the moment to moment experience of seeing.

297
00:39:40,668 --> 00:39:46,833
We're clinging to those atoms of colour that are being strung together to form the concept tree.

298
00:39:48,367 --> 00:39:51,070
This is to cling to the sensory process.

299
00:39:52,211 --> 00:39:54,896
In this case, the eye and seeing.

300
00:39:58,519 --> 00:40:00,061
But clinging is painful.

301
00:40:00,983 --> 00:40:04,668
Realising this, we loosen our grip, relax.

302
00:40:05,809 --> 00:40:09,875
It's a relief to let the tree be there, outside of me.

303
00:40:10,936 --> 00:40:12,398
Just a tree, after all.

304
00:40:15,382 --> 00:40:18,306
But after a while, a niggling doubt sets in.

305
00:40:19,146 --> 00:40:22,731
How is it we know what is there outside of ourselves?

306
00:40:25,076 --> 00:40:29,943
To our dismay, perhaps, we sense that we are now clinging to the notion there.

307
00:40:32,286 --> 00:40:43,382
It's pleasant to think of there being an external world, something I'm not solely responsible for, something I can let go of, ignore when I wish to.

308
00:40:45,353 --> 00:40:51,063
And yet I would be very dismayed to find the tree was not there when next I looked outside my window.

309
00:40:53,967 --> 00:40:59,396
Sadly, I have to admit that I've now gone and attached myself to the sense object.

310
00:41:00,257 --> 00:41:01,820
In this case, the tree.

311
00:41:03,864 --> 00:41:09,353
I'm projecting part of this delusive construct of me outside of myself.

312
00:41:10,699 --> 00:41:16,050
And at the moment it's very bound up with the concept of the tree that grows outside my window.

313
00:41:20,559 --> 00:41:26,148
Clinging to the sense doors, we locate ourselves as here within our bodies.

314
00:41:27,751 --> 00:41:33,382
Clinging to the sense object, we locate ourselves as there in the outside world.

315
00:41:34,898 --> 00:41:37,242
Both attempts to cling are painful.

316
00:41:38,063 --> 00:41:41,528
As we let go of these concepts, equanimity grows.

317
00:41:42,391 --> 00:41:49,342
Sensations and perceptions associated with both here and there slide from head to heart.

318
00:41:49,762 --> 00:41:53,530
We're no longer interested in defining these as one or the other.

319
00:41:54,471 --> 00:41:57,717
It's as if the boundaries to the self grow permeable.

320
00:41:58,844 --> 00:42:03,489
The heart can now include aspects of the outer world, such as the tree.

321
00:42:04,251 --> 00:42:06,032
If I were to ask, where am I?

322
00:42:06,052 --> 00:42:19,889
I would answer that I'm not located at a particular spot, but as a nebulous consciousness, larger than my body, hovering somewhere in between my inner and outer worlds.

323
00:42:22,773 --> 00:42:32,143
When we identify as the observer of experience in this way, we're identifying with consciousness, that which knows experience.

324
00:42:33,583 --> 00:42:40,570
It's the birdwatcher in the hide, a very beautiful state of being, very worthy.

325
00:42:42,954 --> 00:42:52,222
At least on this side of liberation, however, it's still a conditioned state, a composite knowing of several sensations and feelings.

326
00:42:54,092 --> 00:43:05,804
To take another step along the path, we let that observer melt into its underlying nature, the momentary knowing of a sensation, feeling or mind state.

327
00:43:10,528 --> 00:43:20,539
When we can resist all temptations to locate ourselves either here within our inner world or there in the outer world,

328
00:43:21,329 --> 00:43:24,411
or in between as the equanimous observer.

329
00:43:25,614 --> 00:43:37,126
Then there will be in the seen only the seen, in the heard only the heard, in the sensed only the sensed, in the cognized only the cognized.

330
00:43:39,869 --> 00:43:42,311
The body and mind function perfectly.

331
00:43:43,614 --> 00:43:46,757
We can interact intelligently with the world.

332
00:43:47,237 --> 00:43:50,121
The only thing that's missing is the sense of self.

333
00:43:52,210 --> 00:43:54,012
The blackbird sings in the tree.

334
00:43:55,195 --> 00:43:55,815
We know this.

335
00:43:56,496 --> 00:43:57,378
Hearing happens.

336
00:43:58,338 --> 00:43:59,460
But no one hears.

337
00:44:00,523 --> 00:44:01,423
No one knows.

338
00:44:04,869 --> 00:44:08,755
I lend with the epitaph for Bahia spoken by the Buddha.

339
00:44:12,601 --> 00:44:18,690
Where water, earth, fire and wind have no footing.

340
00:44:20,577 --> 00:44:22,699
There the stars don't shine.

341
00:44:24,443 --> 00:44:26,226
The sun isn't visible.

342
00:44:28,409 --> 00:44:30,172
There the moon doesn't appear.

343
00:44:31,634 --> 00:44:33,938
There darkness is not found.

344
00:44:35,940 --> 00:44:43,512
And when a sage, a Brahman through satyasati, has realized this for himself,

